Kyle Harrison and Paul Rabil have carried lacrosse into the 21st century. 

Venturing into the USA Lacrosse Magazine vault, one encounters visual proof of the duo’s impact. Combined, they’ve appeared on the cover 10 times, including once together.

As @uslacrosse celebrates its 25th anniversary, we celebrated the impact of Rabil and Harrison.
Playoff time. Where history is made.

A champion decided only once a year. 52 weeks and a lifetime of prep for just 48 minutes. It’s the most difficult thing to achieve in sports.

I grew up dreaming of playing in the Olympics. Lacrosse was once on the world’s stage in 1904 & 1908, then as a demonstration sport at the 1928, 1932 & 1948 games. But as the Olympic criteria evolved, lacrosse was dropped from competition. 

In 1967 the World Lacrosse Championships were formed — our World Cup. They’ve been held all around the world every four years, first with only 5 countries competing, and today with over 90. Proving lacrosse is capable of being back on the biggest stage. 

In 2018 I was asked to join a very passionate committee that was building a proposal to get lacrosse back into the Olympics. And today marks a monumental achievement. That dream has become a reality again for the next generation of young lacrosse players around the world. 

I’ll be cheering you on.

On my journey I’ve won and lost championships, business deals and relationships. I’ve set ambitious goals and come up short. I’ve learned that success is built on a foundation of failures, when you choose to rise with unwavering resolve.

It's late night preparation that turns into early-morning drills, and the joy of feeling progress with every, sometimes painful, step forward.

Paired with lessons from the greatest athletes and leaders in the world, I wrote this book to serve as a guide for anyone who wants to overcome obstacles, develop resilience, and cultivate the mindset of a champion. 

A special note of gratitude to @ryanholiday for convincing me to write this despite my imposter syndrome — and contributing to the pages. To @penguinrandomhouse & @creativeartistsagency for their effort, guidance and patience with me. To my family, friends, teammates and coaches who have unknowingly played a significant role in this book. And to every champion who has forged their own way. Our legacies are a tribute to yours. 

“A man who views the world at 50 the same as he did at 20 has wasted 30 years of his life.”
— Muhammad Ali 

Coming in May 2024 📖

play multiple sports. you’ll develop different skills, athletic range, with different teammates, coaching styles, a sharper mind, and a clear path forward. when you retire and grow old like me, you’ll appreciate you went for it. turning 38 and i still feel like a kid playing multiple sports. only with creaky bones and less cartilage. i’m extraordinarily grateful to my parents for getting me into half a dozen rec programs, my siblings for putting up with my shit, teammates & coaches for pushing me every sprint of the way, and each of you for the inspiration to keep going.

To Jay Jalbert, AJ Haugen and Josh Sims: thank you. I watched countless hours of your film and wanted to play like you on the lacrosse field. Your styles helped form mine.

Here’s to watching more film in 2024.
